t5051.text: Ive only mentioned just a very small amount of things effected. There’s so many more. I am fearful for my gorgeous country. I love it here so much. Australia needs our help. We all need to take responsibility.

t5052.text: For me, I’m an outdoor person - I don’t want to go out and sit in a cafe with a coffee or do any outdoor sport/exercise because the smoke is so bad for my lungs. Businesses not burnt will feel the effects from the smoke.

t5053.text: Animals that survive now have to find food and water to survive. But everything is burnt. When the rains come, ash will enter the water ways and starve the fish. There could be algae blooms. A mass kill off. It’s dire times.

t5054.text: Over one billion animals are dead. Also, I can’t even put a number to how many invertebrates have been killed. Entire eco systems - destroyed. This isn’t a “normal” Aussie bushfire where things regenerate quickly - there’s hardly any water - this will take a lot of time.

t5055.text: Was also thinking about so many ramifications- health, environmental and economic. What is this smoke doing to us? What’s in it? How does it effect our bodies? How does it effect our minds?

t5056.text: It smells strong of bushfire outside. And I woke up a few hours ago with a headache. I can only assume that the air quality indoors is quite bad. As soon as I entered my house, I instantly had another headache. I can only imagine what others are experiencing.

t5057.text: It’s been a few hours and Sydney’s air quality is still really bad. I’m one of the lucky ones who can filter the air in my house now. #SydneySmoke #ClimateEmergency #ClimateChangeIsReal #NSWfires #AustraliaBurnspic.twitter.com/ACtKw91KiI
